The result is a meticulously researched tome, documenting incidents as early as the burning of ancient Rome and the many conspiracy theories that plagued the 2016 election.
There’s so much writing about conspiracy theories and subcultures that is really snarky, and I just think there’s been enough of that.
I think people who get involved in conspiracy theories are often doing it in response to social and economic inequalities.
The internet has been around for a while, and it hasn’t necessarily made fringe conspiracy theories more mainstream.
